Gaius Petronius found in his work 3 form which allowed complete expression to the many sides of his active and uncontrolled intellect. Its loose construc- tion is matched by its indifference to any but stylistic reforms ; it draws no moral ; it is solely and properly occupied in presenting an aspect of things seen by a loiterer at one particular corner of the world. What we possess of it is a fragment, or rather a series of excerpts from the fifteenth and sixteenth books, we know not how representative of the original whole.
